# Applying config changes

To activate changes made under `hosts/`, `modules/`, or `overlays/`, always use:

```zsh
nix run .#build-switch
```

Do **NOT** tell the user to run `darwin-rebuild switch --flake .` (with or
without `sudo`) directly. The `build-switch` app (see
`apps/aarch64-darwin/build-switch`) is not just a thin alias — it:

- Exports `NIXPKGS_ALLOW_UNFREE=1`, which this config's unfree
  packages/casks need to build.
- Builds the closure first as the normal user (`nix build`), then only uses
  `sudo` to activate via `./result/sw/bin/darwin-rebuild` — invoking
  `darwin-rebuild` from the just-built result rather than whatever is on
  `PATH`/`/run/current-system`, working around
  [nix-darwin#1457](https://github.com/nix-darwin/nix-darwin/issues/1457).
- Cleans up the `./result` symlink afterward.

Other equivalent flake apps, also documented in `README.md`:

- `nix run .#build` — build only, no activation (validate changes).
- `nix run .#rollback` — interactive rollback to a prior generation.
- `nix run .#clean` — garbage-collect generations older than 7 days.

Only reach for raw `darwin-rebuild` commands for things `build-switch`
doesn't cover, e.g. `darwin-rebuild --list-generations` or switching to an
explicit generation number.
